$$\begin{split} \angle SRQ&=180^{\circ}-\angle SQR-\angle RSQ \\\ &=180^{\circ}-130^{\circ}-\angle RSQ \\\ & =50^{\circ}-\angle RSQ. \end{split}$$

Since $l\|k$, we know that $\angle RSQ$ and $\angle SRQ$ are supplementary. So,
$$\begin{split} \angle RSQ+\angle SRQ&=180^{\circ} \\\ \Rightarrow\qquad \angle RSQ&=180^{\circ}-\angle SRQ \\\ &=180^{\circ}-(50^{\circ}-\angle RSQ) \\\ \Rightarrow\qquad 2\angle RSQ&=130^{\circ} \\\ \Rightarrow\qquad \angle RSQ&=65^{\circ}. \end{split}$$

Therefore,
$$\begin{split} \angle SRQ&=50^{\circ}-\angle RSQ \\\ &=50^{\circ}-65^{\circ} \\\ &=\boxed{15^{\circ}}. \end{split}$$
